to enable conjugate gaze?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cranial nerves III, IV, V","Cranial nerves II, III, IV","Cranial nerves III, V, VI","Cranial nerves III, IV, VI","Cranial nerves IV, V, VI"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecranial nerves III (oculomotor), IV (trochlear), and VI (abducens)\u003C/strong\u003E are connected by the medial longitudinal fasciculus to coordinate eye movements. These three nerves control all six extraocular muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerves III, IV, V\u003C/strong\u003E includes cranial nerve V (trigeminal) which is not involved in eye movement, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ecranial nerves III, V, VI\u003C/strong\u003E also incorrectly includes cranial nerve V which is sensory/motor to face but not involved in eye movement. \u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerves II, III, IV\u003C/strong\u003E includes cranial nerve II (optic) which carries visual information but does not control eye movement. \u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerves IV, V, VI\u003C/strong\u003E is missing cranial nerve III which is essential for most eye movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medial longitudinal fasciculus allows these three motor nerves to work together to produce smooth, coordinated eye movements and maintain visual fixation during head movement via the vestibulo-ocular reflex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The medial longitudinal fasciculus connects and coordinates cranial nerves III (oculomotor), IV (trochlear), and VI (abducens) to enable conjugate eye movements.","The vestibulo-ocular reflex maintains visual fixation during head movement through coordinated action of these three cranial nerves.","These three cranial nerves control all six extraocular muscles necessary for coordinated eye movements."],"references":["Fiester P, Baig SA, Patel J, Rao D. An Anatomic, Imaging, and Clinical Review of the Medial Longitudinal Fasciculus. J Clin Imaging Sci. 2020 Dec 18;10:83. doi: 10.25259/JCIS_49_2020. PMID: 33408958; PMCID: PMC7771398.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98110"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16304"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98110"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T15:16:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T15:17:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8995"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116114"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading"